## PROJECT-SPECIFIC STANDARDS

For the Simple Key-Value Store project:

*   Implement a basic persistent key-value store that supports `SET` and `GET` commands using append-only storage.
*   The implementation must follow the specified functionality and support black-box testing using Gradebot.
*   The program needs to accept user input on STDIN and output on STDOUT in the form of simple commands:
    *   `SET <key> <value>`
    *   `GET <key>`
    *   `EXIT`
*   All writes must be persisted to disk immediately using append-only writes to a file named `data.db`.
*   Data must remain consistent after restarting the program. On startup, replay the log to rebuild the in-memory index.
*   Implement a custom in-memory index structure to store key-value pairs. Do not rely on built-in dictionary/map types from your language’s standard library. Ensure that “last write wins” semantics are enforced (the latest SET for a key replaces any previous value).
*   The persistence format for the key-value store should be one line per SET command: "SET key value\n" (key is one word, value is rest of line after the space after key). The key should be separated by a space, and the value can contain spaces.
*   The project must be implemented in Java.
*   Ensure compatibility with Java 8. Use `Paths.get()` instead of `Path.of()`. Compile with `--release 8` to ensure compatibility.

## WORKFLOW & RELEASE RULES

*   Use Git for version control to track progress and commits throughout development.
*   Tag the final working version of the code with `project`.
*   Ensure the repository is public so that it can be viewed.
*   Include a screenshot of the Gradebot output named `gradebot_screenshot.png` in the repository, with identifying information (like your EUID) visible.

